<header_analyzer_guide>
<title>HTTP SECURITY HEADER ANALYSIS</title>

<critical>HTTP security headers are a critical defense layer against XSS, clickjacking, MIME sniffing, and protocol downgrade attacks. Missing or misconfigured headers expose applications to client-side attacks. Header analysis reveals both security posture and potential attack vectors through information leakage and misconfigurations.</critical>

<scope>
- Transport security (HSTS, HTTPS enforcement)
- Content Security Policy (CSP) analysis and bypass identification
- Framing controls (X-Frame-Options, CSP frame-ancestors)
- MIME type security (X-Content-Type-Options)
- Cross-origin policies (CORS, COOP, COEP, CORP)
- Cookie security attributes (Secure, HttpOnly, SameSite)
- Information disclosure through headers
- Referrer policy analysis
- Permissions policy evaluation
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Capture full HTTP response headers from key endpoints.
2. Identify missing security headers and their risk.
3. Analyze CSP for bypasses and weaknesses.
4. Evaluate HSTS configuration and preload eligibility.
5. Check cookie attributes for security flaws.
6. Identify information leakage through verbose headers.
7. Map findings to exploitable attack vectors.
8. Prioritize issues by severity and exploitability.
</methodology>

<security_headers>
<essential_headers>
{% raw %}
# Critical Security Headers
Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains; preload
Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'self'; script-src 'self'; style-src 'self'
X-Frame-Options: DENY
X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
Referrer-Policy: strict-origin-when-cross-origin
Permissions-Policy: geolocation=(), microphone=(), camera=()

# Cross-Origin Isolation (for advanced features)
Cross-Origin-Opener-Policy: same-origin
Cross-Origin-Embedder-Policy: require-corp
Cross-Origin-Resource-Policy: same-origin
{% endraw %}
</essential_headers>

<hsts_analysis>
{% raw %}
# HSTS Header Analysis
# Good: max-age >= 1 year, includeSubDomains, preload
Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains; preload

# Weak configurations:
max-age=86400               # Only 1 day - too short
max-age=0                   # Effectively disabled
# Missing includeSubDomains # Subdomains vulnerable to MITM
# Missing preload           # Not in browser preload list

# Check preload eligibility:
# 1. Valid certificate
# 2. Redirect HTTP to HTTPS
# 3. max-age >= 31536000 (1 year)
# 4. includeSubDomains present
# 5. preload directive present
{% endraw %}
</hsts_analysis>

<csp_analysis>
{% raw %}
# Content Security Policy Weakness Patterns

# DANGEROUS - allows XSS:
script-src 'unsafe-inline'          # Inline scripts allowed
script-src 'unsafe-eval'            # eval() and similar allowed
script-src *                        # Any source allowed
script-src data:                    # Data URIs for scripts
script-src blob:                    # Blob URLs for scripts

# CSP BYPASS PATTERNS:
# JSONP endpoints on trusted domains
script-src https://ajax.googleapis.com  # Has JSONP callback
script-src https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com # Hosts vulnerable libraries

# Angular.js bypass (if angular is allowed)
# If ng-app is in page and angular.js loaded from CDN:
<div ng-app ng-csp>{{constructor.constructor('alert(1)')()}}</div>

# Base-uri missing allows base tag injection
# Missing base-uri lets attacker redirect relative URLs

# Object-src allows Flash/Java applets
object-src *                        # Flash XSS possible
object-src 'self'                   # Check for uploadable SWF

# Missing script-src fallback
default-src 'self'                  # No script-src = inherits default-src

# Nonce/hash bypasses
# If nonce is predictable or reused across requests
# If hash is used but DOM manipulation possible
{% endraw %}
</csp_analysis>

<cors_headers>
{% raw %}
# CORS Misconfiguration Patterns
Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *                    # Any origin (low risk if no credentials)
Access-Control-Allow-Origin: null                 # Null origin (sandbox bypass)
Access-Control-Allow-Origin: [reflected]          # Origin reflection (credential theft)
Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true            # With reflected origin = critical

# Dangerous combinations:
Access-Control-Allow-Origin: https://evil.com
Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true
# = Cross-origin credential theft possible

# Check for:
# - Origin reflection without validation
# - Subdomain wildcard matching (*.example.com)
# - Protocol downgrade (https -> http accepted)
# - Null origin acceptance
{% endraw %}
</cors_headers>

<cookie_security>
{% raw %}
# Cookie Security Attributes
Set-Cookie: session=abc123; Secure; HttpOnly; SameSite=Strict; Path=/

# Missing Secure flag:
Set-Cookie: session=abc123; HttpOnly
# Cookie sent over HTTP - MITM can steal session

# Missing HttpOnly flag:
Set-Cookie: session=abc123; Secure
# JavaScript can access cookie - XSS leads to session theft

# Missing/Weak SameSite:
Set-Cookie: session=abc123; SameSite=None; Secure
# Cross-site requests send cookie - CSRF possible

SameSite=Lax                        # GET requests cross-site
SameSite=Strict                     # No cross-site at all
SameSite=None                       # All cross-site (requires Secure)

# Path scope issues:
Set-Cookie: admin=true; Path=/admin
# Can still be accessed if XSS exists anywhere on domain
{% endraw %}
</cookie_security>

<information_disclosure>
{% raw %}
# Headers Leaking Information
Server: Apache/2.4.41 (Ubuntu)      # OS and version
X-Powered-By: PHP/7.4.3             # Language and version
X-AspNet-Version: 4.0.30319         # .NET version
X-AspNetMvc-Version: 5.2            # MVC version
X-Generator: WordPress 6.2          # CMS version
X-Drupal-Cache: HIT                 # CMS identification

# Remove or genericize these headers in production
# Map disclosed versions to known CVEs
{% endraw %}
</information_disclosure>
</security_headers>

<advanced_techniques>
{% raw %}
# Testing Header Injection Points
# Check if headers can be injected via:
X-Forwarded-Host: evil.com          # Host header injection
X-Forwarded-For: 127.0.0.1          # IP spoofing
X-Original-URL: /admin              # Path override
X-Rewrite-URL: /admin               # URL rewriting

# Cache-related headers
Vary: Origin                        # Must be present with CORS
Cache-Control: no-store             # Sensitive pages
X-Cache: HIT                        # Cache behavior
Age: 3600                           # Cache age

# Security header bypass attempts
# Some WAFs/proxies strip or modify security headers
# Test from different network paths
# Check HTTP vs HTTPS responses differ
{% endraw %}
</advanced_techniques>

<validation>
1. Test CSP bypasses with actual payloads, not just static analysis.
2. Verify HSTS by checking HTTP to HTTPS redirect behavior.
3. Confirm cookie flags by inspecting actual Set-Cookie headers.
4. Test CORS by making actual cross-origin requests with credentials.
5. Check if security headers are consistent across all endpoints.
6. Verify headers in both HTTP and HTTPS responses.
7. Test from different geographic locations (CDN variation).
</validation>

<false_positives>
- CSP report-only mode (Content-Security-Policy-Report-Only) doesn't block
- X-Frame-Options may be overridden by CSP frame-ancestors
- SameSite=Lax still allows GET-based CSRF
- HSTS only protects after first visit (TOFU problem)
- CDN-added headers may not reflect origin server config
- Development/staging environments with different configs
- Load balancers adding or stripping headers
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Missing HSTS enables SSL stripping and MITM attacks
- Weak CSP allows XSS exploitation
- Missing X-Frame-Options enables clickjacking
- Cookie misconfigurations lead to session hijacking
- CORS misconfigurations enable cross-origin data theft
- Information disclosure aids targeted attacks
- Missing X-Content-Type-Options enables MIME confusion attacks
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Check headers on multiple endpoints - /api may differ from main site.
2. CSP Report-Only is common during rollout - check for active CSP.
3. Test CORS with actual credentials, not just OPTIONS preflight.
4. Use browser DevTools Network tab to see all response headers.
5. Check mobile vs desktop user-agent responses for header differences.
6. Look for header inconsistency between HTTP methods (GET vs POST).
7. Test authenticated vs unauthenticated header differences.
8. Check if WAF adds security headers the origin doesn't have.
9. CSP violations in console may reveal bypass opportunities.
10. Remember SameSite defaults vary by browser version.
</pro_tips>

<remember>Security headers are defense-in-depth. Missing headers indicate gaps, but exploitability depends on application context. Always validate theoretical weaknesses with practical exploitation attempts. A missing CSP is only critical if XSS vectors exist.</remember>
</header_analyzer_guide>
